# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1909-chicago-cubs-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1878 Chicago White Stockings season** was the seventh season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third in the National League and the first at Lakefront Park.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 30–30.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] The **1909 Chicago Cubs season** was the 38th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 34th in the National League and the 17th at West Side Park.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs won 104 games but finished second in the National League, 6½ games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs had won the pennant the previous three years and would win it again in 1910.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] Of their 104 victories, 97 were wins for a Cubs starting pitcher; this was the most wins in a season by the starting staff of any major league team from 1908 to the present day.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] The 104 wins was the most by any team in Major League Baseball history by a team that failed to finish first—a record that would be unbroken for more than a century.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] The record was equaled by the 1942 Brooklyn Dodgers and eventually broken by the 2021 Dodgers, who won 106 games but finished a game behind the San Francisco Giants in the NL West.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] To date, the Cubs' 104 wins is the most in Major League Baseball history by a team that failed to make the postseason.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] The legendary infield of Joe Tinker, Johnny Evers, Frank Chance, and Harry Steinfeldt was still intact, but it was the pitching staff that excelled.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs pitchers had a collective earned run average of 1.75, a microscopic figure even for the dead-ball era.
[src:1909-chicago-cubs-season/1909-chicago-cubs-season] Three Finger Brown was one of the top two pitchers in the league (with Christy Mathewson) again, going 27–9 with a 1.31 ERA.
